simple-web-page/.body:
Create a simple web page
Lets dive in and create the simplest possible webs page.  We will then cover what each of the pieces of the web pages does

Note Create a new file called index.html in your favourite editor and add the following code

&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;!-- Files containing styles will be added here later --&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;

    &lt;h1&gt;Simple web page&lt;/h1&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      This is a little bit of content inside a paragraph tag.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      We can include links to other websites, 
      like &lt;a href=&quot;https://google.co.uk&quot;&gt;Google&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;!-- The image tag is self-contained, 
         it uses a closing / rather than a closing tag --&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/kungfu-poh.gif~c200&quot; /&gt;

  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;


Hint The parts that make up this simple web page are explained in this section.

simple-web-page/html.html.body:
HTML
The html tag tells the browser about the type of file it is loading, so the browser can make decisions on how it presents the rest of the information.
The type of file is typically a HTML file, although it could be other formats such as text (.txt) or JSON (.json)
&lt;html&gt;

&lt;html&gt;

Actually, the latest versions of the HTML language, HTML5, also uses the DOCTYPE tag to define what kind of file it is.
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;

&lt;/html&gt;


You can also practice your HTML language on the W3 Schools web app

simple-web-page/head.html.body:
Head
This is where you define information about the page, as well as including any external style file or Javascript libraries.
This section does not show directly in the web page, however any styles you include in this section may affect how the body of the content is shown.
The head section is added using the following tags
&lt;head&gt; 

&lt;/head&gt;

The head tags are placed within the html tags that are at the start and end of the file
&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt;

  &lt;/head&gt;

&lt;html&gt;

Linking Stylesheets
The head section typically including styles that are defined in other files.  By putting files into other files it helps you manage those styles more effectively
If we have multiple pages or mutiple different websites, then it can be valuable to split the style definitions into multiple styles, reflecting the divisions of those styles.  Having seperate files can also be a performance boost, especially if visitors only browse one area of a site (as they dont have to load different styes).  Although if we have to load multiple files for each page, this does slow down a page as each request for a file has a slight performance hit.

In this workshop we will just use styles from a library called Bootstrap, which we will link from the head section.

simple-web-page/body.html.body:
Body
This is the section where the content of your page goes.
The body is section of the web page that you see in the browser.
The body section is added using the following tags
&lt;body&gt; 

&lt;/body&gt;

The body tags are placed within the head tags which in turn are inside the html tags that are at the start and end of the file.
&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt; 

  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;

  &lt;/body&gt;

&lt;html&gt;

simple-web-page/paragraph.html.body:
Paragraph
The p tag represents paragraphs in the text content of your web page.
Browsers automatically add some white space (a margin) before and after a paragraph, so its a simple way to group relevant text content together.
&lt;p&gt;This is a single line paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is another paragraph that is quite long and contains multiple lines.  As it is so long it will wrap the lines of the text as it displays it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  Anything more than a single space   between words is ignored, even after a full stop.
  Tags be put on the same line as the content they define, or for block tags like paragraphs, they can be put on the lines before and after.
&lt;p&gt;

simple-web-page/comments.html.body:
Comments
You may want to add information for others working on the web page as a comment.  Or you may wish to temporarily comment out some of the HTML code in your file to help you fix a problem with your website or see an alternative layout.
Anything inside the comment tag is simply ignored by the browser, so wont be shown on the web page.
Comments are defined using the following tag
&lt;!-- Anything between these tags is ignored by the browser --&gt;

In this example a we have decided to exclude an image from being displayed on our page.  As we add or remove the comment from the image we can see if the page looks better with or with out it.
&lt;!-- Do not display this at the moment
&lt;img src=&quot;pic_mountain.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Mountain&quot; style=&quot;border=0;&quot;&gt;
--&gt;

adding-styles/.body:
Adding Basic Styles
So far our simple web page is lacking any real kind of awesomeness...
We can start to fix this by adding styles to our content.  Styles can include different fonts, size and colour of text.

Note  Replace your simple website with a basic website for Poh, using some basic styles to the web pate.  Then reload the page in your browser to see the changes

&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;!-- Files containing styles will be added here later --&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body style=&quot;background-color:powderblue;&quot;&gt;

    &lt;h1 style=&quot;color:blue;text-align:center;&quot;&gt;Simple web page&lt;/h1&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      Hello, my name is &lt;strong&gt;Poh&lt;/strong&gt; and I am a Panda who loves Kung Fu.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/kungfu-poh.gif&quot;
         style=&quot;float:right;&quot; /&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Career&lt;/h2&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      I work for a family run noodle soup business that I run with my dad.  We provide nutritious soup and dough balls for the community we live in.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Hobbies&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      I love to spend my time learning Kung Fu.  I also collect memorabilia on the
      &lt;a href=&quot;http://kungfupanda.wikia.com/wiki/Furious_Five&quot;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Furious Five&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Where to find me&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      I currently live in the
      &lt;a href=&quot;http://kungfupanda.wikia.com/wiki/Valley_of_Peace&quot;&gt;Valley of Peace&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;!-- The image tag is self-contained, it uses a closing / rather than a closing tag --&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/valley-of-peace.jpg&quot;
         alt=&quot;The Valley of Peace&quot;
         style=&quot;width:600px;height=480px;&quot; /&gt;

  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;


Hint These are just a few examples of styles, some of which make the design better, some styles make the design look worse.  You can spend a lot of time getting the styles right for your website.
Luckily there are lots of libraries of styles, like Bootstrap, that you can use to make your website look awesome with a lot less effort.

adding-styles/inline-styles.html.body:
Inline Styles
The simplest way to add styles is to add them directly to the HTML tags used to define the structure of your page.

Hint Although inline styles are the simplest approach, the more styles you add and the more pages you create for your website, the more effective it is to put these files into a seperate file, called a Stylesheet.

The HTML Style Attribute
Setting the style of an HTML element is done with the style attribute.
The HTML style attribute has the following syntax:
&lt;tagname style=&quot;property:value;&quot;&gt;

Examples
&lt;h1 style=&quot;color:blue;&quot;&gt;This is a heading&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color:red;&quot;&gt;This is a paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;

using-a-stylesheet/.body:
Using a Stylesheet
Instead of putting styles directly into the HTML file, we can simplify things by putting the styles into their own file.  This file is called a Stylesheet.
By having styles in one stylesheet, hey can be used for all your web pages.
Linking to a Stylesheet
To include the styles from a stylesheet in a web page you need to use the link tag.

Note Create a new stylesheet file for your styles an then add that stylesheet to your html file

With your favourite editor, create a file called styles.css inside a new sub-directory called css
Add the following styles to the styles.css file.
/* Simple style definitions */


/* Define a style for the body tag */
body{
    background-color:powderblue;
}


/* Define a style for all h1 tags */
h1{
    text-align: center;
    color:blue;
}


/* Define a style for a specific identity,
in this case an image */

#kungfu-poh-img{
    height:100px;
    width:100px;
    float:right;
}


/* Define a style for a specific identity,
in this case an image */

#valley-of-peace-img{
    width:600px;
    height:480px;
}

Link the new stylesheet
Add the stylesheet to the index.html page by including the following line in between the head tags
&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;css/styles.css&quot;&gt;

Removing the inline styles
You can remove the inline styles from the index.html file now, so that file should look like this:
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;!-- Files containing styles --&gt;
    &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;css/styles.css&quot;&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;

    &lt;h1&gt;Simple web page&lt;/h1&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      Hello, my name is &lt;strong&gt;Poh&lt;/strong&gt; and I am a Panda who loves Kung Fu.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/kungfu-poh.gif&quot;
         alt=&quot;Poh practising his Kung Fu moves - animated gif&quot;
         id=&quot;kungfu-poh-img&quot; /&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Career&lt;/h2&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      I work for a family run noodle soup business that I run with my dad.
      We provide nutritious soup and dough balls for the community we live in.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Hobbies&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      I love to spend my time learning Kung Fu.  I also collect memorabilia on the
      &lt;a href=&quot;http://kungfupanda.wikia.com/wiki/Furious_Five&quot;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Furious Five&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Where to find me&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      I currently live in the
      &lt;a href=&quot;http://kungfupanda.wikia.com/wiki/Valley_of_Peace&quot;&gt;Valley of Peace&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;!-- The image tag is self-contained, it uses a closing / rather than a closing tag --&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/valley-of-peace.jpg&quot;
         alt=&quot;The Valley of Peace&quot;
         id=&quot;valley-of-peace-img&quot; /&gt;

  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

Now, reload the index.html file in your browser and you should see the same

using-a-stylesheet/defining-styles.html.body:
Defining Styles in a Stylesheet
You can define styles for you html file using several different methods

Using the html tag name
Using a unique Id
Using a Class name

Using an html tag name
You can specify one or more styles for a specific html tag, such as h1, body or p.  This will apply the styles to all those tags throughout the web page.
This means you can easily add a style to make all your headings look the same, eg all have the same font, all be bold, all be the same size, etc.
In our example we defined a background colour for our website using the body tag and made all our h1 headings be centred and shown in the colour blue
We can do the same in our style sheet:
/* Define a style for the body tag */
body{
    background-color:powderblue;
}


/* Define a style for all h1 tags */
h1{
    text-align: center;
    color:blue;
}

As we are using the html tags, we do not need to change anything in our html file.
If you want to apply the same styles to multiple html tags, you can simply put them in a comma separated list:
/* Define a style for the body tag */
body{
    background-color:powderblue;
}


/* Define a style for all h1 tags */
h1,h2,h3{
    text-align: center;
    color:blue;
}

Using a unique Id
We can define a style or set of styles to apply to anything by using a unique name called an Id.
We use a # character followed by a unique name to define the Id.  Then in curly brackets, { } we add the styles we want to apply to the content with this Id.
Here is an example of three styles we are applying to anything with the Id kungfu-poh-img
#kungfu-poh-img{
    height:100px;
    width:100px;
    float:right;
}

To use the styles for this Id in our html page, find the relevant tag and at the id to it.
So in this case as our style is for a particular image, we find the img tag in our html file and update it to include an id
&lt;img src=&quot;images/valley-of-peace.jpg&quot;
     alt=&quot;The Valley of Peace&quot;
     id=&quot;valley-of-peace-img&quot; /&gt;

Classes of styles
If you have a group of things you want to apply styles to, you can assign them all a class name.  So if you wanted to apply styles to a group of images, rather than give each image a unique id, you can use a class.
You can of course define styles for the img tag, however this would apply to all img tags.  A class can be used to apply styles to a specific set of img tags.
In the following example, all these images can have the same styles applied to them by using the img.friends name.
&lt;div class=&quot;col-sm-3&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- Friends Oogway --&gt;
         &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;images/friends-oogway.png&quot;
                 alt=&quot;Friends Oogway&quot;
                 class=&quot;friends&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
       &lt;/div&gt;

       &lt;div class=&quot;col-sm-3&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- Friends Shifu --&gt;
         &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;images/friends-shifu.jpg&quot;
                 alt=&quot;Friends Shifu&quot;
                 class=&quot;friends&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
       &lt;/div&gt;

       &lt;div class=&quot;col-sm-3&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- Friends Tigress --&gt;
         &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;images/friends-tigress.jpg&quot;
                 alt=&quot;Friends Tigress&quot;
                 class=&quot;friends&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
       &lt;/div&gt;

So in the CSS file we can define styles for this img.friends class as follows:
img.friends{
    height:96px
    width:96px
}

bootstrap/get-bootstrap.html.body:
Get Bootstrap
Assuming you will always have an Internet connection when creating your page, the simplest way to add bootstrap is to include a link to the Bootstrap files stored in a Content Delivery Network.
You can also download the files and put them in the same directory

Note Add Bootstrap to your project by adding the following lines between the &amp;lt;head&amp;gt; tags in your file.

&lt;!-- Latest compiled and minified CSS --&gt;
&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/css/bootstrap.min.css&quot; integrity=&quot;sha384-BVYiiSIFeK1dGmJRAkycuHAHRg32OmUcww7on3RYdg4Va+PmSTsz/K68vbdEjh4u&quot; crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;

&lt;!-- Optional theme --&gt;
&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/css/bootstrap-theme.min.css&quot; integrity=&quot;sha384-rHyoN1iRsVXV4nD0JutlnGaslCJuC7uwjduW9SVrLvRYooPp2bWYgmgJQIXwl/Sp&quot; crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;

&lt;!-- Latest compiled and minified JavaScript --&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/js/bootstrap.min.js&quot; integrity=&quot;sha384-Tc5IQib027qvyjSMfHjOMaLkfuWVxZxUPnCJA7l2mCWNIpG9mGCD8wGNIcPD7Txa&quot; crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

Content Delivery Network (CDN)
A content delivery network holds any large or common content from your website, such as images and styles, in a number of computers across different geographical regions.
When someone visits your website they get the images &amp; styles from the nearest computer to them, typically saving a lot of time getting the website.
This means that when someone views your web page it should be really fast.

make-page-responsive/add-bootstrap.html.body:
Add Bootstrap
In order to use Bootstrap we need to add it to our index.html file.
Adding the Bootstrap files via a Content Delivery Network (CDN)
Lets add the Bootstrap files so we can start applying the styles

Note Update the contents of the head tag in your index.html file to include Bootstrap styles, theme and Javascript

&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;!-- Files containing styles --&gt;

    &lt;!-- Bootstrap from the Content Delivery Network (CDN --&gt;

    &lt;!-- Latest compiled and minified CSS --&gt;
    &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot;
          href=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/css/bootstrap.min.css&quot;
          integrity=&quot;sha384-BVYiiSIFeK1dGmJRAkycuHAHRg32OmUcww7on3RYdg4Va+PmSTsz/K68vbdEjh4u&quot;
          crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;

    &lt;!-- Optional theme --&gt;
    &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot;
          href=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/css/bootstrap-theme.min.css&quot;
          integrity=&quot;sha384-rHyoN1iRsVXV4nD0JutlnGaslCJuC7uwjduW9SVrLvRYooPp2bWYgmgJQIXwl/Sp&quot;
          crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;

    &lt;!-- Latest compiled and minified JavaScript --&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/3.3.7/js/bootstrap.min.js&quot;
            integrity=&quot;sha384-Tc5IQib027qvyjSMfHjOMaLkfuWVxZxUPnCJA7l2mCWNIpG9mGCD8wGNIcPD7Txa&quot;
            crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;!-- Our stylesheet for our own styles --&gt;
    &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;css/styles.css&quot;&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

We have not changed anything as yet by adding Bootstrap, but now we can start using Bootstrap from our index.html file.

make-page-responsive/summary-with-jumbot.body:
Summary With Jumbotron
Lets add the top part of our design that holds the brief summary of Poh&#39;s life to the web page.
We will use a container to hold this summary and use the Jumbotron component of Bootstrap within that container.

Note First lets remove some of the html code we do not need in index.html

&lt;h1&gt;Simple web page&lt;/h1&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;
      Hello, my name is &lt;strong&gt;Poh&lt;/strong&gt; and I am a Panda who loves Kung Fu.
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;img src=&quot;images/kungfu-poh.gif&quot;
         alt=&quot;Poh practising his Kung Fu moves - animated gif&quot;
         id=&quot;kungfu-poh-img&quot; /&gt;

Now lets add the container and Jumbotron to the page, along with our image of Poh doing kungfu

Note Add the following code to the index.html file, on the line after the body tag.

&lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;h1 id=&quot;website-title&quot;&gt;The Story of Poh&lt;/h1&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;jumbotron&quot;&gt;
          &lt;div class=&quot;pull-right&quot;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&quot;images/kungfu-poh.gif&quot;
                 id=&quot;kungfu-poh-img&quot; &gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;&lt;!-- .pull-right--&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;
              Hello, my name is &lt;strong&gt;Poh&lt;/strong&gt; and I am a Panda who loves Kung Fu.
              I love to watch the Furious Five in action at the Jade palace.
            &lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;&lt;!-- .jumbotron --&gt;

